      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">⚠️ Important Note on Tile Availability</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The tile bag contains only <span class="text-white font-medium">one each of J, K, Q, X and two Z tiles</span>. Words requiring duplicate rare tiles (like two K tiles for BLACKJACKING) would need a blank tile in practice, which scores zero for that letter. The table shows theoretical maximum base scores.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">2 Letters — QI (11 Points)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 2-Letter Champion</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">QI</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">11 points — Q(10) + I(1)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">The vital force or life energy in Chinese philosophy. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL. The single most important word for competitive Scrabble players — it lets you play the Q without needing a U.</p>
      </div>

      <p>QI is not just the highest-scoring 2-letter word — it is arguably the most strategically vital word in the entire game. The Q tile is worth 10 points but infamously difficult to play because only one U exists in the standard bag. QI solves this elegantly: park the Q next to any I on the board and collect 11 points. In competitive play, knowing QI can be worth 20+ points when you factor in the alternative of getting stuck with Q at game end (a 10-point penalty).</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Strategy:</span> Always play QI early if you draw Q without U. Holding the Q hoping for a U costs you turns and rack flexibility. The 11-point score is modest, but freeing your rack is worth far more in future turns.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">3 Letters — ZAX (19 Points)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 3-Letter Champion</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">ZAX</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">19 points — Z(10) + A(1) + X(8)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">A hand tool for cutting and trimming roofing slates. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL. Combines the two highest-value non-Q tiles with the most common vowel.</p>
      </div>

      <p>ZAX pairs the game's two premium consonants (Z=10 and X=8) alongside A, the most abundant vowel with 9 tiles in the bag. Drawing both Z and X together is rare but not impossible. When it happens, ZAX fires both powerhouse letters in a single play rather than waiting for separate opportunities. Other strong 3-letter contenders include JAX (17pts, SOWPODS only) and ZAP (14pts).</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">ZAX</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">19pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">JAX</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">17pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">ZAP</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">14pts</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">QAT</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12pts</span></span>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">4 Letters — JAZZ (29 Points)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 4-Letter Champion</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">JAZZ</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">29 points — J(8) + A(1) + Z(10) + Z(10)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">A genre of music originating in early 20th-century New Orleans. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL. Requires both Z tiles from the bag.</p>
      </div>

      <p>JAZZ delivers 7.25 points per letter — an extraordinary ratio unmatched at any other length. You need both Z tiles (only two in the bag) plus the J, meaning three of the game's most valuable consonants on one rack simultaneously. The probability of holding J+Z+Z at any point is roughly 1 in 200, but when it happens, you can swing a game instantly — especially on a premium square where JAZZ on a double word becomes 58 points.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Strategy:</span> If you draw J + Z early, consider holding both while fishing for the second Z. The 29-point payoff (before premium squares) is worth patience — especially if a double or triple word score is accessible on the board.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">5 Letters — JAZZY (33 Points)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 5-Letter Champion</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">JAZZY</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">33 points — J(8) + A(1) + Z(10) + Z(10) + Y(4)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Having the character or style of jazz; lively and bright. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL. The J+Z+Z+Y combination represents the highest base score achievable in five letters.</p>
      </div>

      <p>JAZZY extends JAZZ by adding Y (worth 4 points), bumping the total to 33 — the peak of the "points per tile" curve for practical play at 6.6 points per letter. At five letters, you still have two tiles remaining on your rack for future plays. JAZZY is common enough in everyday English that most players already know it, making it both memorable and immediately playable when the tiles align.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">33 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Base score</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">6.6</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Points per tile</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">99 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">On triple word</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">6 Letters — JAZZED (32 Points)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 6-Letter Champion</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">JAZZED</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">32 points — J(8) + A(1) + Z(10) + Z(10) + E(1) + D(2)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">To be excited or enthusiastic; past tense of jazz. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL.</p>
      </div>

      <p>JAZZED adds E(1) and D(2) to the JAZZ root. Interestingly, it scores less than 5-letter JAZZY because D+E totals 3 points versus Y alone at 4. This demonstrates a key Scrabble insight: longer words do not always score more. Suffix tiles can dilute the per-letter average. Still, JAZZED is the undisputed 6-letter champion — no other combination of six SOWPODS-valid letters beats it.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">✓ Playability Rating: Medium</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Requires J + both Z tiles + A + E + D. With 9 A tiles, 12 E tiles, and 4 D tiles in the bag, the supporting letters are abundant. The bottleneck is always drawing J + Z + Z together.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">7 Letters — JAZZING (33 Points + 50 Bingo Bonus)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 7-Letter Champion + Bingo!</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">JAZZING</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">33 base + 50 bingo = 83 total — J(8) + A(1) + Z(10) + Z(10) + I(1) + N(1) + G(2)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Present participle of jazz; playing or dancing to jazz music. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL. As a 7-letter word played from a full rack, this earns the 50-point bingo bonus.</p>
      </div>

      <p>JAZZING is special. At 7 letters, it qualifies for the 50-point bingo bonus, making its effective score 83 points — nearly triple its base value. This is the single highest-scoring bingo by base tile value. Drawing J+A+Z+Z+I+N+G requires all seven specific tiles on your rack simultaneously, which is extraordinarily rare. But when the stars align, JAZZING on a triple-word score with the bingo bonus would be 149 points in a single turn.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">33 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Base score</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">+50 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Bingo bonus</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">83 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Effective total</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
