      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">8 Letters — QUIZZIFY (41 Points)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 8-Letter Champion</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">QUIZZIFY</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">41 points — Q(10) + U(1) + I(1) + Z(10) + Z(10) + I(1) + F(4) + Y(4)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">To make into or subject to a quiz. Valid in SOWPODS. This combines Q, both Z tiles, F, and Y for maximum scoring density in 8 letters.</p>
      </div>

      <p>QUIZZIFY marks a leap in scoring because it brings the Q (10 points) alongside both Z tiles and two 4-point letters (F and Y). At 41 points base, it beats JAZZING despite being one letter longer. In a real game, playing QUIZZIFY as a bingo would net 91 points (41 + 50 bonus) — an extraordinary single-turn score. The main constraint is that this word requires Q, U, both Z tiles, F, and Y on your rack simultaneously with I tiles.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-red-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">✗ Playability: Very Low</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Requires Q + U + Z + Z + F + Y + two I tiles. The probability of holding this exact rack is astronomically small. This is theoretical maximum territory — know it for trivia, not for practical play.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">9 Letters — QUIZZICAL (39 Points)</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">📊 Score Breakdown</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Q(10)+U(1)+I(1)+Z(10)+Z(10)+I(1)+C(3)+A(1)+L(1) = 39</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">📖 Definition</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Indicating mild or amused puzzlement. Valid in SOWPODS and TWL.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>QUIZZICAL is a familiar English word meaning "showing puzzlement or amusement." At 39 points, it combines Q and both Z tiles with relatively common supporting letters. While it scores slightly less than QUIZZIFY (39 vs 41), it is far more recognizable. In tournament play, QUIZZICAL as a bingo would net 89 points — devastating if placed across premium squares. The word requires 9 consecutive open spaces on the board, which limits placement options.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">10–11 Letters — Entering Theoretical Territory</h2>

      <p>At 10+ letters, we enter purely theoretical territory. These words are valid in SOWPODS but essentially impossible to play in a real game. They require too many specific tiles and too many consecutive open squares on the board. Still, they represent the mathematical ceiling for each length.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">QUIZZIFIED (10 letters, 43 pts):</span> Q(10)+U(1)+I(1)+Z(10)+Z(10)+I(1)+F(4)+I(1)+E(1)+D(2). Past tense of quizzify. Requires 10 open squares plus the same rare tile combination as QUIZZIFY plus extra letters.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">QUIZZIFYING (11 letters, 46 pts):</span> Q(10)+U(1)+I(1)+Z(10)+Z(10)+I(1)+F(4)+Y(4)+I(1)+N(1)+G(2). Present participle of quizzify. At 46 points base, this would theoretically score 96 with a bingo bonus — but it cannot be played from a fresh rack since it needs 11 tiles.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Why 8+ Letter Words Still Get Bingos</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Words longer than 7 letters can still earn the bingo bonus — you just need tiles already on the board. If QUIZ is already played and you add -ZIFY using all 7 rack tiles to make QUIZZIFY, you earn the +50 bonus. This is called <span class="text-white font-medium">playing through</span>.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">12–15 Letters — The Legendary Maximum Words</h2>

      <p>These are the Mount Everest of Scrabble scoring — words that push the theoretical ceiling as high as it can go. None have ever been played in competitive tournament history in their full form, but they are all valid SOWPODS entries.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">BLACKJACKING (12 letters, 34 pts):</span> B(3)+L(1)+A(1)+C(3)+K(5)+J(8)+A(1)+C(3)+K(5)+I(1)+N(1)+G(2). To strike with a blackjack. Requires two K tiles and two C tiles — the bag has only one K, so a blank would be needed in practice.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">OBJECTIVIZING (13 letters, 37 pts):</span> O(1)+B(3)+J(8)+E(1)+C(3)+T(1)+I(1)+V(4)+I(1)+Z(10)+I(1)+N(1)+G(2). To make objective. Uses J, Z, V, C, and B — five premium tiles in one word.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">PHOTOOXIDIZING (14 letters, 39 pts):</span> P(3)+H(4)+O(1)+T(1)+O(1)+O(1)+X(8)+I(1)+D(2)+I(1)+Z(10)+I(1)+N(1)+G(2). A chemistry term for light-catalysed oxidation. Combines X, Z, H, and P power tiles.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 15-Letter Champion — The Famous One</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">OXYPHENBUTAZONE</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">41 points — O(1)+X(8)+Y(4)+P(3)+H(4)+E(1)+N(1)+B(3)+U(1)+T(1)+A(1)+Z(10)+O(1)+N(1)+E(1)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">A non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug. Valid in SOWPODS. The most famous word in Scrabble lore — the theoretical highest-scoring play across a triple-word-score row has been calculated at 1,778 points in perfect conditions.</p>
      </div>

      <p>OXYPHENBUTAZONE is the most celebrated word in Scrabble trivia. It uses all 15 spaces across the board and combines X(8), Z(10), Y(4), P(3), H(4), and B(3) — six premium tiles in a single word. The base score of 41 points is actually matched by 8-letter QUIZZIFY, which shows that raw letter density matters more than length. But OXYPHENBUTAZONE's fame comes from the theoretical maximum game score: if played across all premium squares in perfect alignment, it could score over 1,700 points. This has never happened in any recorded game.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">41 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Base score</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">15</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Letters used</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">1,778</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Theoretical max with premiums</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">0</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Times played in tournaments</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Bingo Zone — Why 7+ Letters Change Everything</h2>

      <p>The 50-point bingo bonus transforms the scoring landscape for 7+ letter words. A modest 7-letter word scoring 15 points in base value becomes 65 points with the bonus — often more than even JAZZY without premium squares. This is why competitive players obsess over bingo frequency rather than raw tile values.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Achievable Bingos</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">SATIRE stems (RETINAS, NASTIER, etc.) score 7-12 base + 50 bonus. Experts average 2-3 per game because these use common tiles.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Theoretical Only</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">JAZZING, QUIZZIFY, and longer words require specific rare tiles. Most players will never draw these combinations in their lifetime of play.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The practical takeaway: memorize common bingo stems (SATIRE, RETINA, LADIES) for consistent 60-80 point turns, and keep JAZZING in your back pocket for the one-in-a-thousand game where J+A+Z+Z+I+N+G appears on your rack. Frequency beats maximum in long-term scoring.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Practical Takeaways — What to Actually Memorize</h2>

      <p>Not all of these words deserve equal study time. Here is the practical hierarchy ranked by how likely you are to actually play them:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🟢 Must-Know (You Will Play These)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">QI (11pts) — You will draw Q without U regularly. This is non-negotiable knowledge for any serious player.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🟢 Should-Know (Occasional Opportunities)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">ZAX (19pts), JAZZ (29pts), JAZZY (33pts) — Drawing Z+X or J+Z+Z happens a few times per hundred games. Be ready.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🟡 Good-to-Know (Rare but Impactful)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">JAZZED (32pts), JAZZING (83pts with bingo) — You might see these tile combinations once every few hundred games. Worth knowing for the big moment.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔴 Trivia Only (Never Happening in Practice)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">QUIZZIFY, QUIZZICAL, OXYPHENBUTAZONE — Fun facts for word game enthusiasts but not practical study material. Focus on common bingo stems instead.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Maximum Possible Score Fantasy</h2>

      <p>What would a perfect game look like if you could somehow play only maximum-scoring words at every turn? Scrabble players have long debated the theoretical ceiling. The current record for a single competitive game is around 830 points, but mathematical models suggest a perfect game with ideal tile draws and board setups could approach 3,000+ points.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-cyan-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🧮 The Perfect Game Model</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">A theoretical perfect game would need: every play to land on premium squares, multiple bingos per game, and opponents who conveniently open up triple-word-score lanes. The mathematical maximum for a single turn (OXYPHENBUTAZONE across triple-word squares with cross-scoring) has been calculated at <span class="text-white font-medium">1,778 points</span> — more than most players score in their best full game.</p>
      </div>

      <p>The reality is far more modest. Top tournament players average 400-450 points per game, with their highest-scoring games reaching 700-800 points. The gap between theoretical maximums and practical play reveals something important: consistency beats flashiness. A player who scores 30-40 points per turn for 15 turns will outperform someone chasing JAZZY who gets stuck with unplayable tiles for multiple turns.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">The Lesson:</span> These maximum words are aspirational markers, not practical targets. The best players win through rack balance, board control, and bingo frequency — not by chasing triple-Z combinations that appear once in a lifetime.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Score Efficiency — Points Per Tile by Length</h2>

      <p>One of the most interesting patterns in this data is how points-per-tile efficiency changes with word length. Shorter words with power tiles dominate in raw efficiency.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">2L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">5.5 pts/tile</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">3L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">6.3 pts/tile</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">4L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">7.25 pts/tile</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">5L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">6.6 pts/tile</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">6L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">5.3 pts/tile</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">7L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">4.7 pts/tile</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">8L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">5.1 pts/tile</span></span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm"><span class="text-white font-bold">15L</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">2.7 pts/tile</span></span>
      </div>

      <p>The sweet spot is clear: 4-letter words offer the best points-per-tile ratio (JAZZ at 7.25), while 15-letter words have the worst efficiency (OXYPHENBUTAZONE at 2.7 per tile). This makes intuitive sense — longer words must use common low-value letters (E, I, N, O, T) as connective tissue, diluting the per-tile average even when high-value tiles are included.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">JAZZ (4 letters, 29 points) has nearly the same base score as the 12-letter BLACKJACKING (34 points). <span class="text-white font-medium">Four tiles scoring almost as much as twelve</span> tells you everything about how power tiles concentrate value in short words.</p>
      </div>

